Currently, I don&#39;t think there&#39;s a default way to do this.  There&#39;s
probably two steps to get there:

1) Create a feature enhancement request for JUnit to allow a test
class to link back to the suite in whose context it must run.

2) Create a feature enhancement request for Eclipse to honor such a link.

In the meantime, I fear you&#39;re stuck with some sort of lazily set-up
solution, with a @BeforeClass on the individual test class that runs
the suite&#39;s BeforeClass code if it hasn&#39;t already been run.

Or, a custom Runner that does the same...

   David Saff

On 3/9/07, frbaxter1 &lt;frank@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I have a set of tests that must always be configured before they can
&gt; be executed.  I did this using a Suite like this:
&gt;
&gt; @RunWith(DynamicTestSuite.class)
&gt; public class AllTests
&gt; {
&gt;   @BeforeClass
&gt;   public static void beforeEverything()
&gt;   {
&gt;     ...
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   @AfterClass
&gt;   public static void afterEverything()
&gt;   {
&gt;     ...
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; This works great whenever I run my tests using this class.  However,
&gt; when one of my tests fails, I go right click on it and run it
&gt; individually.  Once I do that, the Eclipse plugin just runs that
&gt; class, it completely ignores the fact that it came from a suite. My
&gt; individual test has no knowledge of the test setup, so the test fails
&gt; because the setup was not done properly.
&gt;
&gt; Is there a way to get the Eclipse plugin to always run the suite
&gt; @BeforeClass method, even if it&#39;s running a single test?
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m using Eclipse 3.2, with JUnit 4 installed.
